# Frontend Structure and Documentation Rule

Prefer functional React components, hooks, and plain functions over classes unless a class provides clear value.

Use JSDoc for exported functions, custom hooks, API client functions, shared utilities, context providers, reducers, complex components, and functions with side effects.

For TypeScript, do not repeat obvious type information already present in the function signature. Use comments to explain responsibility, side effects, invariants, security constraints, or architecture boundaries.

Document exported classes when used. A class docstring should explain what the class represents, what responsibility it owns, and any important side effects or invariants.

Document constructor parameters only when they are not obvious from TypeScript types or when construction has side effects.

Document public methods on exported classes when their behavior, side effects, errors, or return values are not obvious.

Do not add JSDoc to trivial local handlers, obvious presentational components, one-line helpers, or private implementation details unless the behavior is non-obvious.

Keep React components focused. Avoid combining data fetching, transformation, complex state management, and rendering in one component. Extract API calls, custom hooks, pure helpers, and presentational components as needed.

Keep API clients separate from UI components.

Keep frontend state transitions explicit and testable where practical.